d legal philosophy of the 1990s; his recent work on memory, forgiveness, and recognition; as well as his enduring interests in religious language and the problem of evil. The contributors not only explain the central concepts and structures of Ricoeur's philosophy, but they also bring him into dialogue with his contemporaries, including Sartre, Heidegger, Gadamer, Habermas, Rawls, and Lyotard. Reading Ricoeur demonstrates the central role of Paul Ricoeur in the development of twentieth-century philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourgeois, Patrick L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDauenhauer, Bernard P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJervolino, Domenico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, David M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKearney, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlemm, David E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaCocque, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRasmussen, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReagan, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchweiker, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct